# Core Conceptual Frameworks

## Shack Architecture: Modular Extension Components

The FloatMesh project reimagines browser extensions through FLOAT's "cathedral to shack" transformation paradigm. Unlike monolithic browser extensions (cathedrals) that attempt comprehensive functionality, FloatMesh embraces the "shack" philosophy—small, modular components that each serve a focused purpose while interconnecting through a shared mesh protocol.

Each "shack" (DevTools panel, content script hook, background orchestrator, BBS shell) exists as a discrete component that can function independently yet participates in the larger ritual ecosystem. This approach reflects FLOAT's core insight that liminal technologies thrive at the boundaries between structure and chaos, allowing for both reliable foundations and emergent behaviors.

```javascript
// Shack #5: Chat-Gremlin - minimal, focused component example
(() => {
  const seen = new Set(); 
  let lastTs = 0;

  // MutationObserver watches for new assistant replies
  new MutationObserver(muts => {
    muts.forEach(m => m.addedNodes.forEach(node => {
      if (!(node instanceof HTMLElement)) return;
      const el = node.querySelector('[data-testid="assistant-response"]');
      if (el) {
        const text = el.innerText.trim();
        // Send to the mesh with unique ID and timestamp
        sendMesh('loamdrop', text);
      }
    }));
  }).observe(document.querySelector('[data-testid="conversation-turn-list"]'), 
             { childList:true, subtree:true });
})();
