ignore those with the most needs all too frequently.","highlight_tags":[],"document_tags":["autism","inbox ND"],"document_author":"roryreckons.blog"}},{"id":887413118,"score":0.011363636363636364,"attributes":{"document_author":"Evan Schultz","document_category":"books","document_title":"Misc Things to Return to","highlight_note":"","highlight_plaintext":"Absolutely. Here’s the extracted list of just the chunk titles from the message above:\n\t1.\tLLM Response Pattern Analysis\n\t2.\tProposed Solutions for LLM Interaction Friction\n\t3.\tImplementation Recommendations for FLOAT Interface\n\t4.\tChroma Collection Structure for FLOAT\n\t5.\tThe “Everything is Rot” Philosophy\n\t6.\tThe Rot Cycle in Knowledge Management\n\t7.\tThe Rotfield Village Metaphor\n\t8.\tFLOAT System Philosophy\n\t9.\tFLOAT as a Ritual Stack\n\t10.\tRedux Inspiration in FLOAT\n\t11.\tLLM Interaction Friction Analysis (detailed)\n\t12.\tProductive vs. Wasteful Friction\n\t13.\tFalse Urgency and Recovery Cycles\n\t14.\tDaily Logs as Navigation System\n\t15.\tFLOAT Dispatch Pattern Usage\n\t16.\tMemory and Information Politics","highlight_tags":[],"document_tags":[]}},{"id":155193438,"score":0.011235955056179775,"attributes":{"document_tags":["autistic burnout"],"highlight_note":"","document_author":"autisticscholar.com","document_category":"articles","document_title":"Burnout and Expectations - Autistic Scholar","highlight_plaintext":"We should instead set high expectations for autistic and neurodivergent people to reach their own personal potential in areas like academic achievement, employment, and autonomy and independence.  Within the “zone of proximal development,” the area of development just beyond a person’s current ability, the area that challenges us to learn but doesn’t overwhelm us, we need to allow autistic people opportunities to learn new skills and to make our own choices.4  Wherever that area might be.","highlight_tags":[]}},{"id":144967813,"score":0.011235955056179775,"attributes":{"document_author":"roryreckons.blog","highlight_plaintext":"Major ways this effect influences us in everyday life","document_category":"articles","highlight_tags":[],"highlight_note":"","document_title":"Auditory Processing With ADHD or Autism","document_tags":[]}},{"id":465105025,"score":0.011111111111111112,"attributes":{"document_author":"@NikkiSiapno on Twitter","document_title":"Learning Web Development...","highlight_note":"","document_tags":[],"highlight_tags":[],"highlight_plaintext":"Learning web development? These 5 websites will accelerate your learning (for free):","document_category":"tweets"}},{"id":150102016,"score":0.01098901098901099,"attributes":{"highlight_tags":[],"document_title":"For an ADHD Diagnosis, T...","highlight_plaintext":"Ultimately, we need to place more value on how it FEELS to be an ADHDer, so professionals and those who are undiagnosed can recognise it. We especially need to amplify POC voices, and build a better understanding of how gender socialisation influences ADHD presentation.","document_author":"@AdhdAngsty on Twitter","document_category":"tweets","document_tags":["inbox ND"],"highlight_note":""}},{"id":244737707,"score":0.01098901098901099,"attributes":{"highlight_tags":[],"highlight_note":"","document_author":"@commaficionado on Twitter","document_category":"tweets","highlight_plaintext":"5. \"Autism is a learning disability\"\n\nIt's not, in and of itself, but there is a fairly high rate of co-occurence and those with learning disabilities are a big part of our community who are often overlooked so this is a myth that needs careful consideration.","document_title":"Myths About #Autism That...","document_tags":[]}},{"id":174261549,"score":0.010869565217391304,"attributes":{"highlight_plaintext":"Taking Learning and Development to the Strategic Level","highlight_tags":["the upskilling imperative - taking learning and development to the strategic level"],"document_author":"Shelley Osborne","document_category":"books","highlight_note":"","document_tags":["story time","ramble import","work vault","import - work vault","inbox L&D","learning and development"],"document_title":"The Upskilling Imperative"}},{"id":86607487,"score":0.010869565217391304,"attributes":{"highlight_tags":[],"document_tags":["ND twitter"],"highlight_plaintext":"THE ADHD RELATIONSHIP TO PAST & FUTURE\n(aka “Not Now”)\n\nBecause this experience of time can be so unpredictable, we also frequently struggle with\nEvaluating, Anticipating, &/or Predicting the…\n\n・Duration of tasks & events\n・Temporal distance between events\n/5 https://t.co/fw3hT7FRW9","document_author":"@ThinckFinck on Twitter","document_category":"tweets","highlight_note":"","document_title":"#ADHD Time Blindness..."}},{"id":196678972,"score":0.010752688172043012,"attributes":{"document_category":"books","highlight_note":"","document_author":"Shelley Osborne","highlight_plaintext":"Presenting Learning and Development to the C-Suite","document_tags":["story time","ramble import","work vault","import - work vault","inbox L&D","learning and development"],"highlight_tags":["pink"],"document_title":"The Upskilling Imperative"}},{"id":76008628,"score":0.010752688172043012,"attributes":{"highlight_plaintext":"I can't stop to think how fucked up it is that trauma related symptoms are often considered common traits of Neurodiversity because growing up ND is so traumatic most of us develop them just by existing","document_category":"tweets","document_title":"I Can't Stop to Think Ho...","highlight_note":"","highlight_tags":[],"document_author":"@ADHDelaide on Twitter","document_tags":[]}},{"id":163050534,"score":0.010638297872340425,"attributes":{"highlight_plaintext":"Challenges for Learning & Development departments\n\n\n\nAccording to CEB, 70% of employees feel that opportunities for learning and development within the company are lacking. It is not enough, not relevant and the learning methods do not fit within todays frame of work.","highlight_tags":[],"document_author":"futurelearningorganisation.com","document_category":"articles","document_title":"6 Factors for Building a Learning Organization","document_tags":["L&D roles","learning culture","learning and development"],"highlight_note":""}},{"id":723677328,"score":0.010638297872340425,"attributes":{"highlight_plaintext":"Activation: organizing tasks and materials, estimating time, prioritizing tasks, and getting started on work tasks. Patients with ADD describe chronic difficulty with excessive procrastination. Often they will put off getting started on a task, even a task they recognize as very important to them, until the very last minute. It is as though they cannot get themselves started until the point where they perceive the task as an acute emergency.\nFocus: focusing, sustaining focus, and shifting focus to tasks. Some describe their difficulty in sustaining focus as similar to trying to listen to the car radio when you drive too far away from the station and the signal begins fading in and out: you get some of it and lose some of it. They say they are distracted easily not only by things that are going on around them, but also by thoughts in their own minds. In addition, focus on reading poses difficulties for many. Words are generally understood as they are read, but often have to be read over and over again in order for the meaning to be fully grasped and remembered.\nEffort: regulating alertness, sustaining effort, and processing speed. Many with ADHD report they can perform short-term projects well, but have much more difficulty with sustained effort over longer periods of time. They also find it difficult to complete tasks on time, especially when required to do expository writing. Many also experience chronic difficulty regulating sleep and alertness. Often they stay up too late because they can’t shut their head off. Once asleep, they often sleep like dead people and have a big problem getting up in the morning.\nEmotion: managing frustration and modulating emotions. Although DSM-IV does not recognize any symptoms related to the management of emotion as an aspect of ADHD, many with this disorder describe chronic difficulties managing frustration, anger, worry, disappointment, desire, and other emotions. They speak as though these emotions, when experienced, take over their thinking as a computer virus invades a computer, making it impossible for them give attention to anything else. They find it very difficult to get the emotion into perspective, to put it to the back of their mind, and to get on with what they need to do.\nMemory: utilizing working memory and accessing recall. Very often, people with ADHD will report that they have adequate or exceptional memory for things that happened long ago, but great difficulty in being able to remember where they just put something, what someone just said to them, or what they were about to say. They may describe difficulty holding one or several things “on line” while attending to other tasks. In addition, persons with ADHD often complain that they cannot pull out of memory information they have learned when they need it.\nAction: monitoring and regulating self-action. Many persons with ADHD, even those without problems of hyperactive behavior, report chronic problems in regulating their actions. They often are too impulsive in what they say or do, and in the way they think, jumping too quickly to inaccurate conclusions. Persons with ADHD also report problems in monitoring the context in which they are interacting. They fail to notice when other people are puzzled, or hurt or annoyed by what they have just said or done and thus fail to modify their behavior in response to specific circumstances. Often they also report chronic difficulty in regulating the pace of their actions, in slowing self and/or speeding up as needed for specific tasks.","highlight_tags":[],"document_tags":[],"document_category":"articles","highlight_note":"","document_author":"www.middleburycenter.com","document_title":"Thomas Brown's Model of Executive Function - Debbie Tracht Coaching"}},{"id":880129644,"score":0.010526315789473684,"attributes":{"highlight_plaintext":"float i,e,R,s;vec3 q,p,d=vec3((FC.xy9.)/r-vec2(1.5),7.);for(q.yz--;i++<99.;){e+=i/1e5;o+=iei/15.vec4(.9,.63,.47,1)/d.y;s=2.;p=q+=deR.1;p=vec3(log2(R=length(p))-p.z,exp2(mod(p.y,p.z)/R),t.1+p.x);for(e=--p.y;s<2e3;s+=s)e+=abs(dot(cos(p.yzxs),sin(ps))/s*.11);}#つぶやきGLSL https://t.co/Ux8jnTPXlW https://t.co/FKUDHEaDxR","highlight_tags":[],"document_tags":[],"document_author":"@YoheiNishitsuji on Twitter","document_category":"tweets","document_title":"Tweets From Yohei Nishitsuji","highlight_note":""}},{"id":86607567,"score":0.010526315789473684,"attributes":{"highlight_plaintext":"RESOURCES TO DIVE DEEPER\n\nADHD & Experiencing Time\nwith @translatingadhd\n\nTo help you get a handle on your own ADHD relationship with time, start with this episode.\nThen listen to the four @translatingadhd episodes after this one.\n19/\nhttps://t.co/KZXxwB3vwZ","document_category":"tweets","document_author":"@ThinckFinck on Twitter","highlight_note":"","document_tags":["ND twitter"],"highlight_tags":[],"document_title":"#ADHD Time Blindness..."}},{"id":149207053,"score":0.010416666666666666,"attributes":{"highlight_plaintext":"Reaction times for ADHDers in computer tasks are...you guessed it...inconsistent.\n\n(...when compared to non-ADHD control group)","document_author":"@robmerki on Twitter","document_title":"Did You Know One of The symptoms of ADHD is intra-individual variability - via robmerki","document_category":"tweets","document_tags":["neurodiverse twitter"],"highlight_tags":[],"highlight_note":""}},{"id":75227510,"score":0.010309278350515464,"attributes":{"highlight_plaintext":"#ADHD is a superpower is a very privileged thing to say\n\nPeople can romanticize Hyperfocus or savant syndrome, there is so much privilege that has to line up for us to be able to play to these strengths, and it's dismissive of the challenges that we still face.","highlight_note":"","document_tags":["my-tweets","neurodiverse twitter","readwiseimport"],"document_author":"@e_p82 on Twitter","document_title":"e_p82 - What's one thing that you wish your Neurotypical partner","document_category":"tweets","highlight_tags":[]}},{"id":182132728,"score":0.010309278350515464,"attributes":{"document_title":"The Upskilling Imperative","document_author":"Shelley Osborne","highlight_plaintext":"Think Like a Marketer to Drive Learning and Development","highlight_tags":["l&d - think like a marketer"],"document_tags":["story time","ramble import","work vault","import - work vault","inbox L&D","learning and development"],"highlight_note":"","document_category":"books"}},{"id":150102017,"score":0.01020408163265306,"attributes":{"document_author":"@AdhdAngsty on Twitter","highlight_tags":[],"document_tags":["inbox ND"],"document_category":"tweets","document_title":"For an ADHD Diagnosis, T...","highlight_note":"","highlight_plaintext":"ADHD has been defined by how much we annoy others around us, whether that be our parents, teachers, or workmates. Screw that. Let's keep sharing our stories on here, and build a better repository of what ADHD feels like, so more of us can get the support they deserve."}},{"id":196678969,"score":0.01020408163265306,"attributes":{"document_title":"The Upskilling Imperative","highlight_note":"","highlight_plaintext":"Learning and Development ROI Is Squishy; We Know This","document_tags":["story time","ramble import","work vault","import - work vault","inbox L&D","learning and development"],"highlight_tags":["pink"],"document_category":"books","document_author":"Shelley Osborne"}},{"id":143013444,"score":0.010101010101010102,"attributes":{"document_category":"tweets","highlight_plaintext":"So, if our ADHD/Neurodiverse behaviours manifested in a way that didn't get recognized as a problem for others, \n\nand if we somehow managed to make it through the school system - we must